	(35,1,'2016-01-29 19:52:25','2016-01-29 19:52:25','On Wednesday the 9th December 2015 President Zuma fired Finance Minister Nhlanhla Nene and installed a relative unknown, Desmond van Rooyen. The Rand dived to a record R15.38/$ after the news. By Sunday evening Pravin Gordhan was re-appointed as Finance Minister. The Rand had breached R16/$ pre the announcement and recovered to the mid R15.50’s on the news of Gordhan’s appointment. Zuma’s blunder cost SA billions!\r\n\r\nAfter reaching a low of R17.82/$ on the 10th January 2016, the Rand has steadily strengthened to close at R15.87/$ on Friday night. It’s clear to see the impact of Nene’s firing on the R/$ exchange rate but what has caused the Rand to strengthen? The first observation is that the Rand was heavily oversold, the reinstatement of Minister Gordhan also went some way in restoring confidence but rather than SA specific factors alone emerging market currencies have strengthened against the US Dollar of late. The Fed’s announcement this week not to increase interest rates and increasingly mixed economic data from the US (indicating a slower rate hiking cycle) has seen the Dollar weaken. These factors coupled with this week’s announcement of our own Monetary Policy Meeting to hike rates by 50 basis points also supported the Rand.\r\n\r\nSA faces many challenges in the years ahead and we may be approaching levels were buying dollars will be attractive on a long-term view. This is also supported by a global equity markets that are not as expensive as they were a few months back.\r\n\r\nAs always we welcome any feedback on our Weekly Review.','R15.87/$','','publish','open','open','','r15-87','','','2016-04-04 19:59:01','2016-04-04 18:59:01','',0,'http://strategiq.co.za/?p=35',0,'post','',0),
