	(38,1,'2016-02-05 19:54:14','2016-02-05 19:54:14','The Bank of Japan recently stunned markets by introducing a negative interest rate policy. This has caused Japanese government bond prices to soar with 10-year yields fast approaching zero (inverse relationship between yield and price). Central Banks set a negative interest rate so that commercial banks will be charged for holding some deposits. The policy is intended to encourage lenders to use their currency reserves to make loans and spur growth. A broad risk is that this will encourage banks to invest in riskier assets to secure a return, driving new asset bubbles.\r\n\r\nThe chart of the week illustrates the 10-year sovereign yields of the worlds largest developed economies, the reduction in yields (making money too cheap) is increasing risks of future potential pain in the form of inflation and asset bubbles. Central banks will need to balance stimulating economic growth with the unintended consequence of encouraging the uneconomical allocation of assets. The spread between South African bonds and developed market bonds (like Japan) has been attractive of late, making the carry trade attractive which in turn should continue to help strengthen the Rand.\r\n\r\nAs always we welcome any feedback on our Weekly Review.','Negative Interest Rates?','','publish','open','open','','negative-interest-rates','','','2016-04-04 19:59:44','2016-04-04 18:59:44','',0,'http://strategiq.co.za/?p=38',0,'post','',0),
