	(49,1,'2016-03-11 20:02:02','2016-03-11 20:02:02','The European Central Bank (“ECB”) cut its deposit rate on Thursday to -0.4%. Five central banks are now in the negative interest rate club: Japan, Denmark, Switzerland and Sweden (and the ECB).\r\n\r\nThe reaction to Super Mario’s (head of ECB Mario Draghi) fresh steps to fight deflation across the Eurozone was mixed. Markets initially rallied and then seemed to digest the underlying concern – are central banks reaching the limits of what monetary policy can do? A more upbeat view of negative rates is how this will likely stimulate the economy. Negative rates should lower the cost of capital and therefore encourage investment, and lower the discount rate on asset prices and therefore boost valuations. The global search for yield continues with the latest policy actions by the ECB.\r\n\r\nGlobal markets were generally buoyed by the ECB’s actions, locally resource counters cooled off from their recent surge.\r\n\r\nAs always we welcome any feedback on our Weekly Review.','The search for yield','','publish','open','open','','the-search-for-yield','','','2016-04-04 20:19:59','2016-04-04 19:19:59','',0,'http://strategiq.co.za/?p=49',0,'post','',0),
