	(81,2,'2016-04-15 13:01:51','2016-04-15 11:01:51','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nChina released their 1<sup>st</sup> Quarter GDP numbers which matched forecasts (6.7% year on-year). The read through was positive pointing towards a “soft” landing scenario as opposed to the feared “hard” landing scenario. Analysts said the data showed China’s economy was stabilising and the impact of monetary stimulus was working. We are concerned by the elevated levels of corporate leverage, the state of the banking system and its ability to deal with NPL\'s (non-performing loans).\r\n\r\nOil producing countries meet in Doha this weekend to agree on an output freeze (production cuts) to prop up crude prices. The prospects of a deal appear high.\r\n\r\nDomestically financial markets and especially the resource sector are benefiting from emerging market flows and the rebound in commodity prices.','Soft Landing?','','publish','open','open','','soft-landing','','','2016-04-20 13:05:50','2016-04-20 11:05:50','',0,'http://strategiq.co.za/?p=81',0,'post','',0),
