	(242,2,'2016-10-08 21:39:30','2016-10-08 19:39:30','Pound Sterling was under renewed pressure this week after Theresa May said that she would trigger article 50 by next March and hinted at a hard Brexit – putting immigration controls at the forefront of EU discussions at the expense of remaining in the single market. With investors worried about the subsequent outlook for the UK economy, the pound is trading at a 31-year low relative to the US Dollar.\r\n\r\nIn global news, investors were cautious ahead of the US payrolls report released on Friday. Data showed that the US economy added 156,000 jobs last month, while the unemployment rate ticked up to 5% as more workers entered the labour market. This number was slightly below expectations.\r\n\r\nOther major news included a flash crash of Pound Sterling in the early hours of Friday morning, dropping by 8% to $1.18 to the US Dollar. The move was attributed to a \'fat finger\', algorithms, and French President, Francois Hollande’s comments that the UK must suffer the consequences of leaving the EU.\r\n\r\nLocally, the JSE All Share Index was softer, ending the week down -0.55%, led by Industrials (-1.10%) and resource shares (-0.42%), whilst the financial sector was only marginally weaker (-0.11%). The rand was volatile, depreciating by 1.05% to the US Dollar and closing at a level of 13.85. It however traded as  low as 13.53 mid-week.\r\n\r\nAs always we welcome any feedback on our Weekly Review.','Pound Sterling Reaches 31-Year Low','','publish','open','open','','pound-sterling-reaches-31-year-low','','','2016-10-08 21:39:30','2016-10-08 19:39:30','',0,'http://strategiq.co.za/?p=242',0,'post','',0),
