 yield and (3) market rating. Currency exposure creates a 4<sup>th</sup> source of return (and risk). Depreciation of the rand and the earnings growth have been the most significant sources of return over all these periods. Currency has therefore been an important contributor to return. As per the chart below, rand depreciation has been a significant contributor to overall return of the MSCI World Index over three, five and ten years, whilst rand strength has been a detractor over a one year period.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_505\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"944\"]<img class=\"size-full wp-image-505\" src=\"http://strategiq.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Picture4.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"944\" height=\"419\" /> Currency has been a significant contributor to long-term performance[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Reason 5:  Diversification mitigates risk</strong>\r\n\r\nAn investor can reduce portfolio risk simply by holding combinations of securities or assets that are not perfectly positively correlated. In other words, investors can reduce their exposure to risk by holding a diversified portfolio (allocating between assets and/or diversifying among securities). Diversification allows for the same expected return with reduced risk.\r\n\r\nAs a South African you are exposed to the SA economy, the consumer and local economics, when these are under pressure there may be other parts of the world with brighter economic prospects.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_507\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"wp-image-507 size-full\" src=\"http://strategiq.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Picture5.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"255\" /> As the saying goes: \"Don’t put all your eggs in one basket\"[/caption]\r\n\r\nIn summary once you have made the logical decision to invest offshore, one needs to decide how much to allocate offshore and the optimal investment strategy to follow. How much should one allocate offshore? Does one take funds physically offshore or make use of asset swap funds? How are the funds held, in one’s name, through a life wrapper or in an offshore Trust? There are many questions to answer, ensure you find the right financial experts to help you make the right choices.','5 additional reasons why you should invest internationally','','inherit','closed','closed','','488-revision-v1','','','2017-06-26 16:56:36','2017-06-26 14:56:36','',488,'http://strategiq.co.za/488-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(509,1,'2017-06-26 16:57:14','2017-06-26 14:57:14','It’s been 22 years since South African’s were first allowed to invest their savings offshore. Since then, there has been a dramatic change in how much money we are legally allowed to transfer overseas.\r\n\r\nFor example, 17 years ago, individuals were only entitled to a lifetime allowance of R750 000, requiring a tax clearance. As of March 2015, anyone can take up to R11 million out of the country every calendar year. (R1 million discretionary allowance, not requiring any tax clearance). Effectively, this means that for the vast majority of South African resident’s exchange controls are no longer an issue and international investment markets are open to South Africans.\r\n\r\nAs South Africans one of the primary reasons for investing internationally is to hedge against socio-economic issues and political risk, the so-called “Zimbabwe” scenario. Whilst these are real risks that investors should consider, we highlight several other reasons to consider offshore investments.\r\n<h3>Reason 1: Access to a much wider investment universe</h3>\r\nThe South African Stock Market (JSE) accounts for approximately 1% of the global stock market (greater than $70 trillion). Investing offshore widens your investment universe to roughly 15 000 listed companies globally while the JSE has just over 400 listed companies. Investing offshore also offers access to global growth sectors like IT (with specialist sub-sectors like semi-conductors) and pharmaceuticals which are either not available on the JSE or have limited investment opportunities.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_490\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"641\" class=\"middle center \"]<img class=\"size-full wp-image-490\" src=\"http://strategiq.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Picture1.jpg\" alt=\"“The JSE only accounts for 1% of global market capitalisation of $74.8 trillion”\" width=\"641\" height=\"149\" /> The JSE only accounts for 1% of global market capitalisation of $74.8 trillion[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h3>Reason 2: SA market is extremely concentrated</h3>\r\nThe top 20 listed companies on the South African stock market represent almost 70% of the overall market capitalization (size) of the entire market. The performance of the top 20 shares therefore dominates the All Share Index returns. Naspers alone accounts for approximately 17% of the All Share Index. This high concentration to few counters increases the risk of a locally invested investment portfolio.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_497\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"247\"]<img class=\"size-full wp-image-497\" src=\"http://strategiq.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Picture2.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"247\" height=\"204\" /> Investing offshore reduces concentration risk[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h3>Reason 3: To match future ‘hard’ currency expenses</h3>\r\nWhilst currency movements can be extremely unpredictable, fundamentally the rand is expected to weaken over time due to the inflation differential between South Africa and its major trading partners.  Over the past 20 years, the rand has depreciated against the US Dollar by 200% (5,6% p.a.); illustrated by the gold trendline in the chart below.\r\n\r\nTherefore, if you want to retire overseas or travel extensively, you have investments to meet future liabilities. This would also apply to children or grandchildren who might want to be educated overseas.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_502\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"728\"]<img class=\"wp-image-502 size-full\" src=\"http://strategiq.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Picture3-1.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"728\" height=\"433\" /> Over the past 20 years, the rand has depreciated by 5.6% on an annualised basis relative to the USD[/caption]\r\n<h3>Reason 4: Currency creates an additional source of return</h3>\r\nTraditionally, sources of equity returns are (1) earnings growth, (2) dividend yield and (3) market rating. Currency exposure creates a 4<sup>th</sup> source of return (and risk). Depreciation of the rand and the earnings growth have been the most significant sources of return over all these periods. Currency has therefore been an important contributor to return. As per the chart below, rand depreciation has been a significant contributor to overall return of the MSCI World Index over three, five and ten years, whilst rand strength has been a detractor over a one year period.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_505\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"944\"]<img class=\"size-full wp-image-505\" src=\"http://strategiq.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Picture4.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"944\" height=\"419\" /> Currency has been a significant contributor to long-term performance[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h3>Reason 5:  Diversification mitigates risk</h3>\r\nAn investor can reduce portfolio risk simply by holding combinations of securities or assets that are not perfectly positively correlated. In other words, investors can reduce their exposure to risk by holding a diversified portfolio (allocating between assets and/or diversifying among securities). Diversification allows for the same expected return with reduced risk.\r\n\r\nAs a South African you are exposed to the SA economy, the consumer and local economics, when these are under pressure there may be other parts of the world with brighter economic prospects.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_507\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"wp-image-507 size-full\" src=\"http://strategiq.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Picture5.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"255\" /> As the saying goes: \"Don’t put all your eggs in one basket\"[/caption]\r\n\r\nIn summary once you have made the logical decision to invest offshore, one needs to decide how much to allocate offshore and the optimal investment strategy to follow. How much should one allocate offshore? Does one take funds physically offshore or make use of asset swap funds? How are the funds held, in one’s name, through a life wrapper or in an offshore Trust? There are many questions to answer, ensure you find the right financial experts to help you make the right choices.','5 additional reasons why you should invest internationally','','inherit','closed','closed','','488-revision-v1','','','2017-06-26 16:57:14','2017-06-26 14:57:14','',488,'http://strategiq.co.za/488-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
