 positive as the economy added 209,000 jobs in July, higher than the expected 180,000, according to Bloomberg. The unemployment rate dropped to 4.3% from 4.4%, matching a 16-year low.\r\n\r\nOn Thursday, the Bank of England Monetary Policy Committee voted to maintain record low interest rates, with the vote for no change coming in as expected. Governor, Mark Carney said Brexit is casting the biggest shadow over the U.K.’s economic outlook, as his confidence in an orderly departure from the European Union starts to fade.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Market Moves of the Week:</strong></p>\r\n<img class=\"size-full wp-image-642 aligncenter\" src=\"http://strategiq.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/Capture-4-August-2017.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"501\" height=\"542\" />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Chart of the Week:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_643\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"521\"]<img class=\"wp-image-643\" src=\"http://strategiq.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/UK-Policy.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"521\" height=\"383\" /> Source: Thomson Reuters. Despite hawkish statements from some policy makers and above-target inflation, the Bank of England\'s MPC voted 6-2 to keep interest rates unchanged at 0.25%, a record low.[/caption]\r\n\r\nAs always we welcome any feedback on our Weekly Review.\r\n\r\nHave a great week!\r\n\r\n<em>Strategiq Capital is an authorised financial services provider (FSP 46624)</em>','Week in Review: Steinhoff goes for controlling stake in Shoprite','','inherit','closed','closed','','639-revision-v1','','','2017-08-05 11:43:49','2017-08-05 09:43:49','',639,'http://strategiq.co.za/639-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(650,2,'2017-08-13 12:41:24','2017-08-13 10:41:24','The JSE All-Share index ended the week 1.41% weaker amid losses in all major sectors. Resources (-1.24%), Industrials (-1.68%), Financials (-1.13%) and SA Listed Property (-0.96%) all ended the week weaker. Investor sentiment fell after president Jacob Zuma survived a motion of no confidence, held via secret ballot in Parliament on Tuesday. The president survived the motion by 24 votes after 198 MPs voted in favour of keeping him as president, against 177 opposing votes. The failure to remove the president will strengthen his position within the party.\r\n\r\nAmid all the political uncertainties, ratings agency Moody’s was set to release a ratings review of South African credit on Friday. Moody’s decided not to release the ratings review on Friday and will release a credit opinion on the 15th of August. This credit opinion is a normal macroeconomic view of a country and does not carry any decision on the countries credit rating.\r\n\r\nGlobally, markets all ended the week softer amid rising tensions between the U.S. and North Korea. The UN Security Council imposed new sanctions on North Korea over the development of their nuclear weapons program. The sanctions, driven by the U.S. and approved by both Russia and China will cut North Korea’s export revenues by a third. This announcement prompted a response by North Korea and they subsequently threatened to fire four of their Hwasong-12 missiles into the seas surrounding the U.S.-held territory of Guam.\r\n\r\nGlobal markets such as the S&amp;P 500 (-1.43%), NASDAQ (-1.50%) and FTSE 100 (-2.69%) all felt the pinch as investors responded to the global tension between the U.S. and North Korea. Subsequently, the gold price surged and ended the week 2.34% stronger. Brent Crude oil ended the week -0,61% softer.\r\n\r\nIn other company news, NYSE-listed Snap Inc. fell short of quarterly earnings expectations and the market did not react kindly. The company behind the messaging service Snapchat fell 13% after releasing their quarterly results. Snap has been coming under pressure from their larger competitors who are offering the same product features that were originally unique to Snapchat.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Market Moves of the Week:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_655\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"495\"]<img class=\"wp-image-655 size-full\" src=\"http://strategiq.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/Aug-13.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"495\" height=\"519\" /> Source: Thomson Reuters[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Chart of the Week:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_660\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"480\"]<img class=\"wp-image-660 size-full\" src=\"http://strategiq.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/Image-1-003.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"480\" height=\"320\" /> U.S. consumer prices remained soft for the fifth continuous month in July, making the Federal Reserves targeted 2.0% annual rate harder to achieve. The consumer price index rose a seasonally adjusted 0.1% in July. Core inflation also rose 0.1%, held down by a decline in new vehicle prices which fell 0.5%, the biggest decline since August 2009. These figures are making it more difficult to see how the Federal Reserve can further hike interest rates.[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAs always we welcome any feedback on our Weekly Review.\r\n\r\nHave a great week!\r\n\r\n<em>The information included above as well as individual companies and/or securities mentioned should not be construed as investment advice, a recommendation to buy or sell or an indication of trading intent on behalf of any Strategiq product. Strategiq Capital is an authorised financial services provider (FSP 46624).</em>','Week in Review: Fury, Fire and Zuma','','publish','open','open','','week-review-fury-fire-zuma','','','2017-08-14 09:14:53','2017-08-14 07:14:53','',0,'http://strategiq.co.za/?p=650',0,'post','',0),
