	(665,2,'2017-08-14 09:16:31','2017-08-14 07:16:31','Late on Friday afternoon Steinhoff released a SENS outlining the proposed listing of Steinhoff’s African retail assets and options to acquire a controlling stake in supermarket operator Shoprite in a share deal worth 35.5 billion rand ($2.6 billion).\r\n\r\nThe new entity Steinhoff Africa Retail Limited (“STAR”), has been established and, with effect from 1 July 2017, owns the African retail assets to be listed. It is anticipated that the listing will be complete by the end of September, subject to market conditions. The African retail brands included in the Listing will comprise Pep in South Africa and the rest of Africa, Ackermans, Speciality division (comprising Dunns, John Craig, Refinery and Shoe City), JD Group (comprising Russells, Bradlows, Rochester, Sleepmasters, Incredible Connection and Hi-Fi Corporation), Steinbuild, Poco South Africa and Tekkie Town (the “African Assets”).\r\n\r\nThe rand fell to a new three-week low against the dollar on Friday as strong U.S. jobs data coupled with local economic and political risks dented investors\' appetite for the currency. The rand, trading at its weakest levels since July 12, has this week also been hit by fears of a third credit rating downgrade to \"junk\" ahead of review by Moody\'s on Aug. 11.\r\n\r\nThe market was also cautious ahead of a vote on a motion of no-confidence in President Jacob Zuma on Aug. 8. If the motion succeeds, Zuma and his entire cabinet would have to step down.\r\n\r\nOn the bourse, stocks ended higher with JSE All-Share index ending the week 1.93% stronger amid gains in Resources (+3.03%), Financials (+2.33%) and Industrials (+1.53%).\r\n\r\nIn the US, the stock market continues its positive momentum, as most of the companies reported better-than-expected earnings in the second quarter. On Wednesday, The Dow Jones climbed above 22,000 for the first time and closed at a record high on Friday.\r\n\r\nThe economic backdrop also remained positive as the economy added 209,000 jobs in July, higher than the expected 180,000, according to Bloomberg. The unemployment rate dropped to 4.3% from 4.4%, matching a 16-year low.\r\n\r\nOn Thursday, the Bank of England Monetary Policy Committee voted to maintain record low interest rates, with the vote for no change coming in as expected. Governor, Mark Carney said Brexit is casting the biggest shadow over the U.K.’s economic outlook, as his confidence in an orderly departure from the European Union starts to fade.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Market Moves of the Week:</strong></p>\r\n<img class=\"size-full wp-image-642 aligncenter\" src=\"http://strategiq.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/Capture-4-August-2017.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"501\" height=\"542\" />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Chart of the Week:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_643\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"521\"]<img class=\"wp-image-643\" src=\"http://strategiq.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/UK-Policy.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"521\" height=\"383\" /> Source: Thomson Reuters. Despite hawkish statements from some policy makers and above-target inflation, the Bank of England\'s MPC voted 6-2 to keep interest rates unchanged at 0.25%, a record low.[/caption]\r\n\r\nAs always we welcome any feedback on our Weekly Review.\r\n\r\nHave a great week!\r\n\r\n<em>he information included above as well as individual companies and/or securities mentioned should not be construed as investment advice, a recommendation to buy or sell or an indication of trading intent on behalf of any Strategiq product. Strategiq Capital is an authorised financial services provider (FSP 46624).</em>','Week in Review: Steinhoff goes for controlling stake in Shoprite','','inherit','closed','closed','','639-revision-v1','','','2017-08-14 09:16:31','2017-08-14 07:16:31','',639,'http://strategiq.co.za/639-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(666,2,'2017-08-14 09:16:53','2017-08-14 07:16:53','<p style=\"text-align: left;\">The JSE All-Share index ended the week 1.33% stronger led by gains in Resources (+6.54%). Industrials (+0.22%), Financials (+0.12%) and SA Property (+0.22%) all ended the week relatively flat.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Resource stocks helped steer the South African share market to its best intra-day level since 2015, while some of the big industrial stocks took a breather after staging a strong rally in recent days.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">The impetus in the resources sector came from various positive earnings reports. One being, Kumba Iron Ore, which reinstated a dividend when reporting its interim results. Kumba shares surged as much as 13% after it declared a R15.97 per share dividend, its first return to shareholders since 2015.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Commodity prices mostly increased, led by a 9.28% increase in Brent Crude. The ZAR weakened 0.79% however it remains 5.31% stronger year to date.</p>\r\nGlobally, the S&amp;P 500 ended the week unchanged (-0.02%), but reached a new record high on Wednesday. While the S&amp;P 500 failed to expand upon its gains from the last two weeks, the Dow Jones Industrial Average rose by 1.16% as company earnings helped propel it higher.\r\n\r\nWith more than half of the companies in the S&amp;P 500 having reported second-quarter results, earnings are up 9.1% year-over-year, signaling that the profit rebound remains intact. The market has rallied 12% in the 4 months following the election, reflecting a shift in economic optimism predicated on president Trump’s pro-growth agenda (tax reform, deregulation, infrastructure stimulus).\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Market Moves of the Week:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_629\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"496\"]<img class=\"wp-image-629 size-full\" src=\"http://strategiq.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/week.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"496\" height=\"519\" /> Source: Thomson Reuters[/caption]\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Chart of the Week:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_632\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"690\"]<img class=\"wp-image-632 size-full\" src=\"http://strategiq.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/weekly-2.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"690\" height=\"469\" /> This week’s advance GDP estimate showed that the US economy expanded at an annualised rate of 2.6% in Q2, beating Fathom’s forecast of 1.9%. Consumption was stronger than expected, with personal consumption expenditures rising 2.8% on an annualised basis.[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAs always we welcome any feedback on our Weekly Review.\r\n\r\nHave a great week!\r\n\r\n<em>he information included above as well as individual companies and/or securities mentioned should not be construed as investment advice, a recommendation to buy or sell or an indication of trading intent on behalf of any Strategiq product. Strategiq Capital is an authorised financial services provider (FSP 46624).</em>','Week in Review: Offshore Earnings on the Rise','','inherit','closed','closed','','628-revision-v1','','','2017-08-14 09:16:53','2017-08-14 07:16:53','',628,'http://strategiq.co.za/628-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(667,2,'2017-08-14 09:17:15','2017-08-14 07:17:15','Nike Inc. released their fourth quarter and full year results in late June 2017. On a full year basis, revenue grew 6% and diluted earnings per share increased 16% to $2.51/share. Results for the quarter came in above the markets expectations. Analyst consensus called for revenue of $8.63bn and $0.50 per share for the quarter, while reported revenue and earnings per share for the quarter were $8.68bn and $0.60 respectively.\r\n\r\nFootwear and apparel had the largest gains in revenue over the year with footwear climbing 6.09% to $21.01bn and apparel grew 6.47% to $9.65bn. Together footwear and apparel account for over 89% of the company’s revenue. Geographically, Greater China and Japan displayed the strongest top line growth of 11.94% and 16.69% respectively.\r\n\r\nTwo key themes have been identified as playing a vital role in Nike’s growth going forward. The themes are the following:\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li>Partnerships and Direct-to-consumer (DTC): Just recently Nike announced partnerships with both Amazon and Instagram. Nike will use Instagram-style posts to start selling their products directly through Instagram. Nike will also offer a product range on Amazon. These both benefit Nike as it opens them up to millions of more potential customers on both Amazon and Instagram as well as allowing Nike to leverage off Amazon’s distribution channels. Both partnerships tie into Nike’s effort to improve DTC revenue. This form of revenue tries to get products directly to the consumer in the most efficient way possible. An example of a DTC initiative paying dividends is a 30% increase in digital commerce sales for the period.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li value=\"2\">International Growth: Nike are continuing to expand internationally. This both diversifies their consumers and allows them to hedge the currency by earning in multiple countries. With increasing emerging market growth, there lies great opportunity for Nike to expand its products and take over global market share in the footwear and apparel markets. By expanding revenue out of the US Nike also benefit from a lower effective tax rate, allowing greater potential returns for shareholders.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<em>he information included above as well as individual companies and/or securities mentioned should not be construed as investment advice, a recommendation to buy or sell or an indication of trading intent on behalf of any Strategiq product. Strategiq Capital is an authorised financial services provider (FSP 46624).</em>','Company Update: DTC Grows Nike\'s Revenues','','inherit','closed','closed','','608-revision-v1','','','2017-08-14 09:17:15','2017-08-14 07:17:15','',608,'http://strategiq.co.za/608-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(668,2,'2017-08-14 09:17:35','2017-08-14 07:17:35','The JSE All-Share index ended the week 1.05% stronger amid gains in Industrials (+1.98%), Financials (+1.85%) and Property (+0.31%). Resources ended the week 1.89% weaker.\r\n\r\nThe two talking points for the week were the SA inflation and interest rate numbers. Firstly,  SA CPI dipped to 5.1% year-on-year in June, a decrease of 0.3% from the previous CPI number. This is the lowest SA inflation has been since November 2015. Secondly, the South African Reserve Bank cut its key rate by 25 basis points, to 6.75%. This is the first time in the last five years that the SA central bank has cut borrowing costs. The decision was made on the back of the lower inflation numbers and the slow growth the SA economy faces.\r\n\r\nLocal retail stocks gained momentum over the week as the lower inflation numbers and interest rate cut put investor confidence back into the sector. Truworths (+7.04%), The Foschini Group (+7.43%) and Mr Price (+5.36%) were some of the retailers that benefited from the economic news.\r\n\r\nGlobal markets had a mixed week of returns. The Dow Jones (-0.27%) ended the week slightly weaker while the S&amp;P 500 (+0,54%), NASDAQ (+1.19%), FTSE 100 (1.01%) and TOPIX (+0.28%) all ended the week stronger.\r\n\r\nThe weakest return over the week was the STOXX 600, which eased 1.73% on the back of a stronger Euro. The Euro strengthened after the ECB left rates unchanged.\r\n\r\nIn other news, Amazon CEO Jeff Bezos has posted his first Instagram video: drone footage of Blue Origin\'s New Glenn rocket production facility. The video ends with the CEO on the roof holding a sign saying \"ROCKET FACTORY COMING SOON\". Blue Origin is Jeff Bezos\'s play at sending people to space at relatively low costs. New Glenn is the company\'s reusable orbital launch vehicle, expected to make its maiden launch test before 2020.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Market Moves of the Week:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_587\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"499\"]<img class=\"wp-image-587 size-full\" src=\"http://strategiq.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/Capture220717.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"499\" height=\"502\" /> Source: Thomson Reuters[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Chart of the Week:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_592\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"952\"]<img class=\"wp-image-592 size-full\" src=\"http://strategiq.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/Chart22.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"952\" height=\"714\" /> The South African Reserve Bank cut its policy rate for the first time in 5 years by 25 basis points to 6.75%. The move reflects a more sluggish GDP growth outlook, as well as improved inflation dynamics.[/caption]\r\n\r\nAs always we welcome any feedback on our Weekly Review.\r\n\r\nHave a great week!\r\n\r\n<em>he information included above as well as individual companies and/or securities mentioned should not be construed as investment advice, a recommendation to buy or sell or an indication of trading intent on behalf of any Strategiq product. Strategiq Capital is an authorised financial services provider (FSP 46624).</em>','Week in Review: SA Rates Cut','','inherit','closed','closed','','581-revision-v1','','','2017-08-14 09:17:35','2017-08-14 07:17:35','',581,'http://strategiq.co.za/581-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(669,2,'2017-08-14 09:17:54','2017-08-14 07:17:54','The JSE All-Share index ended the week 3.27% higher led by gains in Resources (3.16%), Industrials (3.81%), Financials (3.12%) and Property (2.39%). The strong week of trading was a result of weaker US CPI data and the suspension of the mining charter. This led to a stronger rand and a more positive environment for mining stocks. Over the week, the rand appreciated by 2.78% relative to the dollar.\r\n\r\nIn the week ahead, markets will turn to SA inflation and interest rate numbers, which will impact the financial and retail sectors.\r\n\r\nGlobal markets ended the week stronger as second quarter earnings season commences. The Dow Jones (+1.04%), S&amp;P 500 (+1.41%), NASDAQ (+2.59%), STOXX 600 (+1.75%) and FTSE 100 (+0.37%) all ended the week stronger. We expect earnings to continue to rise at a solid, albeit slower, pace through the remainder of the year, as sales are helped by the synchronized global rebound in economic growth and as cost controls remain tight.\r\n\r\nThe technology-heavy NASDAQ ended the week +2.6% higher, its best week since December, after a rebound in technology stocks. Amazon (+2.36%) and Alphabet (+3.84%) were some of the technology large caps to add gains to the index.\r\n\r\nCommodities all ended the week stronger amid gains in Gold (+1.49%), Iron Ore (+3.29%), Platinum (+2.20%) and the Brent Crude (4.71%).\r\n\r\nIn company news, Swedish carmaker<em> Volvo </em>this week moved the motor industry closer to an electric future, by announcing that from 2019, it would only produce pure electric and hybrid cars.\r\n\r\nGlobal sales of electric cars amounted to less than 1% of the market last year, but are expected to grow rapidly. US electric car start-up Tesla confounded motor industry expectations in 2016 by taking nearly 400,000 orders for its $35,000 Model 3 car. General Motors will launch ten electric models by 2020, and Toyota announced its ambition to mass-produce them by 2020.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Market Moves of the Week:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_549\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"495\"]<img class=\"wp-image-549 size-full\" src=\"http://strategiq.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/Picture4.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"495\" height=\"519\" /> <em>Source: Thomson Reuters</em>[/caption]\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Chart of the Week:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_552\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"680\"]<img class=\"wp-image-552 size-full\" src=\"http://strategiq.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/1111-2.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"680\" height=\"383\" /> This chart represents the impact that market timing can have on a portfolios annualised performance between the years 1995 - 2017 (5468 trading days). It illustrates the importance of staying invested over a longer period of time, allowing ample time for asset positions to grow. By missing just 100 of the best trading days the portfolio performance would move from an annualised gain of 15.57% to a loss of -3.00%.[/caption]\r\n\r\nAs always we welcome any feedback on our Weekly Review.\r\n\r\nHave a great week!\r\n\r\n<em>he information included above as well as individual companies and/or securities mentioned should not be construed as investment advice, a recommendation to buy or sell or an indication of trading intent on behalf of any Strategiq product. Strategiq Capital is an authorised financial services provider (FSP 46624).</em>','Week in Review: Staying Invested','','inherit','closed','closed','','548-revision-v1','','','2017-08-14 09:17:54','2017-08-14 07:17:54','',548,'http://strategiq.co.za/548-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(670,2,'2017-08-14 09:18:22','2017-08-14 07:18:22','The JSE ended the week 0.56% higher, the third successive week on the upside, as resources outperformed on a weaker rand despite sharp falls in oil and silver affecting commodities prices.\r\n\r\nHowever, market heavyweight Naspers, ended the week 2.76% lower, as investors raised concerns regarding its recent issuance of a $1bn bond that will partially be used for the settlement of  existing debt.\r\n\r\nResources (+3,61%) and Financials (+0.32%) lead the gain in overall markets, while Industrials ended weaker (-0,46%). The rand weakened 2.62% as political uncertainty and concerns over the central bank\'s independence in recent weeks heightened.\r\n\r\nOffshore, all markets were relatively flat for the holiday shortened week, while Friday\'s lift from the June jobs report was not quite enough to overcome geopolitical and monetary-policy jitters. The S&amp;P 500 (+0.07%), NASDAQ (+0.21%), the Dow Jones (+0.30%) and STOXX 600 (+0.21%) all increased marginally, while the TOPIX decreased 0.30%.\r\n\r\nNext week, inflation and retail sales data will be released on Friday. Investors will review these releases with a critical eye to determine if the weakness witnessed in both of these indicators over the last few months were outliers or if they can reverse trend.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Market Moves of the Week:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_534\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"501\"]<img class=\"wp-image-534 size-full\" src=\"http://strategiq.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/5th-July.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"501\" height=\"512\" /> Source: Thomson Reuters[/caption]\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Chart of the Week:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_540\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"560\"]<img class=\"wp-image-540\" src=\"http://strategiq.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/Picture1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"560\" height=\"421\" /> The US economy added another 222,000 net new payrolls in June according to Friday’s nonfarm payrolls report. Net payroll growth in the previous two months was revised up by a combined 47,000 – the unemployment rate edged higher to 4,4% due to an increase in the labour force.[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAs always we welcome any feedback on our Weekly Review.\r\n\r\n<em>The information included above as well as individual companies and/or securities mentioned should not be construed as investment advice, a recommendation to buy or sell or an indication of trading intent on behalf of any Strategiq product. Strategiq Capital is an authorised financial services provider (FSP 46624).</em>','Week in Review: Nonfarm Payroll','','inherit','closed','closed','','533-revision-v1','','','2017-08-14 09:18:22','2017-08-14 07:18:22','',533,'http://strategiq.co.za/533-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
