	(695,2,'2017-08-27 13:35:14','2017-08-27 11:35:14','The JSE All-Share index ended the week 2.44% stronger amid gains in all major sectors excluding property. Resources (+2.84%), Industrials (+2.55%) and Financials (+2.66%) all ended the week in the positive while SA Listed Property declined (-1.76%). Gains were helped in part by mining stocks‚ which benefited from higher commodity prices.\r\n\r\nIn company specific news, Woolworth\'s reported a disappointing set of results, with its first drop in full-year profits in eight years. The retail environment continues to be under pressure globally as consumerism seems to be going through a technologically driven fundamental change.\r\n\r\nGlobally, markets such as the S&amp;P 500 (+0.72%), NASDAQ (+.079%) and FTSE 100 (+1.06%) all ended the week positive. Brent Crude oil ended the week -0.59% softer.\r\n\r\nWith a third of the year left, the market has turned in a strong performance so far in 2017. U.S. stocks sit near record levels, and international equities have logged double-digit gains for the first time since 2013. And despite the polarizing, if not chaotic, political atmosphere that has characterized much of the year, markets have posted healthy returns with only modest bouts of volatility.\r\n\r\nFurther, the strength in European manufacturing (and thus exports) counteracts views that the strength of the euro might affect economic growth by making Eurozone exports less competitive. Europe’s leading share markets awaited speeches from Federal Reserve chairwoman Janet Yellen and European Central Bank chief Mario Draghi at a gathering of central bankers in the US on Friday afternoon. At the meeting, Yellen said that on the one hand events of the financial crisis demanded action, needed reforms were implemented, and these reforms have made the system safer. However, on the other hand, Yellen cited the likelihood of the all-too-familiar risks of excessive optimism, leverage and maturity transformation re-emerging in new ways that require policy responses. The fact that these risks were mentioned may leave a 2017 rate hike \"on the table.\"\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h5 style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Market Moves of the Week:</strong></h5>\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_696\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"447\"]<img class=\"wp-image-696\" src=\"http://strategiq.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/price-action.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"447\" height=\"482\" /> Source: Thomson Reuters[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h5 style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Chart of the Week:</strong></h5>\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_697\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"457\"]<img class=\"wp-image-697\" src=\"http://strategiq.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/aaa.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"457\" height=\"335\" /> Flash GDP data in the euro area showed that strong growth has spread across the whole of the currency bloc. GDP rose by 0.60% in the euro area as a whole in the second quarter of 2017, or an annual pace of 2.20% up from 1.90% in Q1.[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAs always we welcome any feedback on our Weekly Review.\r\n\r\nHave a great week!\r\n\r\n<em>The information included above as well as individual companies and/or securities mentioned should not be construed as investment advice, a recommendation to buy or sell or an indication of trading intent on behalf of any Strategiq product. Strategiq Capital is an authorised financial services provider (FSP 46624).</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Week in Review: Earnings Growth Outshines Political Volatility','','publish','open','open','','week-review-earnings-growth-outshines-political-volatility','','','2017-08-28 08:31:52','2017-08-28 06:31:52','',0,'http://strategiq.co.za/?p=695',0,'post','',0),
