	(703,2,'2017-09-02 12:10:40','2017-09-02 10:10:40','The JSE All-Share index ended the week lower. Resources (+2.11%) and the SA Listed Property Sector (+1,87%) ended the week in the positive while the Industrial and Financial sectors pulled the overall market down.\r\n\r\nIn company specific news, Steinhoff’s share price was pummelled by allegations relating to its tax and accounting practices. On Thursday afternoon, Steinhoff dismissed the allegations as wrong and misleading which helped reverse some of the earlier losses. The story comes at a difficult time for Steinhoff as it is about to finalise a substantial transaction with Shoprite.\r\n\r\nStatistics South Africa publishes second quarter economic growth data on Tuesday. National Treasury is facing a sharp funding crunch with weak growth, lower tax revenues and bailout to state firms expected to stretch the budget deficit past 4 percent of GDP, upping the likelihood of another round of credit downgrades.\r\n\r\nThe rand continued to strengthen after the United States reported weaker than expected employment growth (US nonfarm payrolls rose a less-than-expected 156,000, missing estimates for a 180,000 rise. The unemployment rate ticked up to 4.4% from July’s 4.3%) diminishing bets of imminent rate hikes by the Federal Reserve.\r\n\r\nGlobal equities firmed this week despite some midweek volatility surrounding North Korea’s missile launch over northern Japan. In the US stocks finished higher for the second week in a row, helped by upwardly revised GDP growth that reached 3% for the first time since 2015. Other tailwinds for the market included a rejuvenated focus on possible tax reform and better-than-expected manufacturing data.  Headwinds, included the devastation brought from Hurricane Harvey, which left at least 39 dead and displaced tens of thousands and is expected to be one of the most expensive natural disasters in US history.\r\n\r\nIn Europe, German chancellor Angela Merkel has joined French president Emmanuel Macron in calling for the creation of a eurozone finance minister in order to increase fiscal integration in the single-currency area. The third and latest round of Brexit negotiations ended on an acrimonious note, with the two sides unable even to agree on whether any progress had been made during the week. There has been no agreement on key issues such as the Northern Ireland border, citizen’s rights and the size of the Brexit divorce payment.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Market Moves of the Week:</strong></p>\r\n<img class=\"size-full wp-image-707 aligncenter\" src=\"http://strategiq.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/weeklkly-table.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"499\" height=\"522\" />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"> Source: Thomson Reuters</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Chart of the Week:</strong></p>\r\n<img class=\"size-full wp-image-708 aligncenter\" src=\"http://strategiq.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/pic33.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"687\" height=\"472\" />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Source: Thomson Reuters.</p>\r\nUS Q2 GDP growth was revised up to 3% from 2,6%. The upward revision reflected an upturn in consumption and investment, partly offset by a downturn in government spending.\r\n\r\nHave a great week!\r\n\r\n<em>The information included above as well as individual companies and/or securities mentioned should not be construed as investment advice, a recommendation to buy or sell or an indication of trading intent on behalf of any Strategiq product. Strategiq Capital is an authorised financial services provider (FSP 46624).</em>','Week in Review: Harvey Havoc','','publish','open','open','','week-review-harvey-havoc','','','2017-09-04 10:29:53','2017-09-04 08:29:53','',0,'http://strategiq.co.za/?p=703',0,'post','',0),
