	(716,2,'2017-09-10 13:47:18','2017-09-10 11:47:18','The JSE All-Share index ended the week lower amid losses in all major sectors. Resources (-1.66%), Industrials (-1.16%), Financials (-2.21%) and SA Listed Property (-0.07%) all ended the week weaker.\r\n\r\nIn company news Dangote Cement – run by Africa’s richest man, Andile Dangote – is considering a bid for South African cement manufacturer PPC Group. PPC are open to reviewing any rival offers to the joint approach by Fairfax Financial Holdings and Afrisam Group. The acquisition would give Dangote a foothold outside of its home market of Nigeria.\r\n\r\nThe rand depreciated by 0.05% over the week relative to the dollar and by 1.80% to the British Pound.\r\n\r\nGlobally, markets all ended the week softer. Aside from the terrible impact hurricanes Harvey and Irma have had on human lives they have also had an impact on the U.S. economy. Jobless claims were reported at their highest level in the last two years. There were 62000 more applicants than the week before. This was attributed to the impact hurricane Harvey has had on workplaces and livelihoods. The US 10-year Treasury yields fell below 2,05% for the first time since November.  The Dow Jones (-0.86%), NASDAQ (-1.17%) and the S&amp;P 500 (-0.61%) all ended the weak softer.\r\n\r\nGlobal equity markets were also impacted but none more than the TOPIX which ended the week 1.61% weaker. The Mountain Day holiday which took place on Friday the 1st of September meant that markets were closed and prevented Japanese investors from responding to the increasing US – North Korean tension.\r\n\r\nIn currency markets the euro reached a two-and-a-half year high against the dollar. This was after ECB President Mario Draghi said that the ECB will have to take the euro’s strength into account when deciding to begin reducing its asset purchase program.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Market Moves of the Week:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_719\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"496\"]<img class=\"wp-image-719 size-full\" src=\"http://strategiq.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/PictureSeptember.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"496\" height=\"519\" /> Source: Thomson Reuters[/caption]\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Chart of the Week: </strong></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_720\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"952\"]<img class=\"wp-image-720 size-full\" src=\"http://strategiq.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/CaptureSAGDP.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"952\" height=\"719\" /> South Africa GDP for the second quarter of the year was 2.5%, indicating the end to a technical recession. The primary industry had a substantial contribution to the growth numbers, with growth of 10.3%. The number one contributing factor was the 33.6% growth in the agriculture sector contributing 0.7 of a percentage point to the overall GDP growth. Despite the growth, South African investment still remains depressed with fixed investment spending declining by 1.1% over the year. This signifies low confidence on a corporate level as companies are not willing to commit capital until the appetite for the economy has improved.[/caption]\r\n\r\nAs always we welcome any feedback on our Weekly Review.\r\n\r\nHave a great week!\r\n\r\n<em>The information included above as well as individual companies and/or securities mentioned should not be construed as investment advice, a recommendation to buy or sell or an indication of trading intent on behalf of any Strategiq product. Strategiq Capital is an authorised financial services provider (FSP 46624).</em>','Week in Review: SA Climbs out of Recession','','publish','open','open','','week-review-sa-climbs-recession','','','2017-09-10 13:47:18','2017-09-10 11:47:18','',0,'http://strategiq.co.za/?p=716',0,'post','',0),
