	(730,2,'2017-09-16 09:51:03','2017-09-16 07:51:03','The JSE All-Share Index ended the week -0.14% lower amid losses in Resources (-0.54%) and Financials (-1.41%). The rand depreciated by 1.69% to the US Dollar, assisting Industrials (+0.53%) to end the week positively. SA Listed Property (+0.35%) also ended the week in positive territory. Aspen Pharmacare Holdings rallied +8.5% on Thursday, after the company posted a 19.0% rise in its FY17 earnings per share (EPS), whilst cement producer, PPC advanced +4.7% after confirming that Dangote Cement proposed a bid to acquire all its shares.\r\n\r\nIn economic news, SA retail sales advanced 1.8%, less than market expectations for an increase of 2.5%. The 2Q17 current account balance to GDP recorded an unexpected drop to a level of -2.4%, worse than market expectations of a -1.9% deficit.\r\n\r\nGlobally, major headline news included Hurricane Irma, rising geopolitical tensions after North Korea launched another ballistic missile over Northern Japan; and the Friday morning tube bombing at Parsons Green in Fulham, London.\r\n\r\nGlobal markets were strong with the Dow Jones (+2.16%), S&amp;P 500 (+1.58%), NASDAQ (+1.39%), Stoxx 600 (+1.38%) and Topix (+2.85%) all ending positively. The only outlier was the UK, with the FTSE 100 (-2.20%) ending the week lower.\r\n\r\nDuring the week, the Bank of England (BoE) kept its key interest rate steady at 0.25% as expected. However, the central bank suggested in its meeting minutes that “some withdrawal of monetary stimulus is likely to be appropriate over the coming months, to cool surging inflation and as British economic growth shows signs of improvement, thanks to a firmer housing market, stronger employment and a rebound in retail and new car sales. UK CPI climbed to 2.9% in August, more than market expectations for an increase of 2.8%.\r\n\r\nIn the US, consumer price inflation increased more-than-expected, amid rising gasoline and rent costs (1.9% vs 1.8% expected). Finally, Chinese economic data disappointed with industrial production recording a rise of 6.0%, less than market expectations for a rise of 6.6%. Retail sales increased 10.1%, also lower than market expectations for a rise of 10.5%.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Market Moves of the Week:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_728\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"500\"]<img class=\"wp-image-728 size-full\" src=\"http://strategiq.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/16-Sept-2017-image.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"500\" height=\"523\" /> Source: Thomson Reuters[/caption]\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Chart of the Week:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_729\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"807\"]<img class=\"wp-image-729 size-full\" src=\"http://strategiq.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/16-Sept-2017-Chart.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"807\" height=\"457\" /> After recently achieving an all-time high price of $5000, Bitcoin the world’s most well-known cryptocurrency and digital payment system tumbled below $3000 in intraday trade on Friday. The pullback stems from one of China’s largest online exchanges who said it would stop handling trades by the end of the month amid a government crackdown on cryptocurrencies. China plans to ban trading of bitcoin and other virtual currencies on domestic exchanges. Prior to the pullback, Bitcoin had risen more than four-fold this year amid greater acceptance of the blockchain technology that underpins the exchange method, global political uncertainty and increased interest in Asia. China accounts for about 23 percent of bitcoin trades and is also home to many of the world’s biggest bitcoin miners, who use vast amounts of computing power to confirm transactions in the digital currency.[/caption]\r\n\r\nAs always we welcome any feedback on our Weekly Review.\r\n\r\nHave a great week!\r\n\r\n<em>The information included above as well as individual companies and/or securities mentioned should not be construed as investment advice, a recommendation to buy or sell or an indication of trading intent on behalf of any Strategiq product. Strategiq Capital is an authorised financial services provider (FSP 46624).</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Week in Review: Bitcoin tumbles as Chinese exchange says it will halt trading','','inherit','closed','closed','','726-revision-v1','','','2017-09-16 09:51:03','2017-09-16 07:51:03','',726,'http://strategiq.co.za/726-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(731,2,'2017-09-24 13:04:41','2017-09-24 11:04:41','The JSE All-Share index ended the week relatively flat (+0.35%). Industrials increased 0.35%, while financials and SA listed property both increased 1.54% and 1.08% respectively. Lastly, resources was the only sector to show losses, decreasing 0.41%.\r\n\r\nOverall, the rand weakened to the USD over the week (0.67%). The currency has been under pressure for much of the week on expectations that US interest rates would rise and South African rates would drop, which meant the yield differential which attracts foreign investors to the local bond market would shrink.\r\n\r\nHowever, the rand traded firmer on Friday after the South African Reserve Bank decided to keep the interest rate stable. Although news that the repo rate will remain unchanged was met with some disappointment, it boosted the rand and bonds.\r\n\r\nIn company news, Sasol came under pressure, falling 5.42% for the week, as they announced that the group wrote off almost R12bn to unwind an empowerment scheme and reported a 15% earnings drop.\r\n\r\nOn a positive note, although recently coming under pressure by the media regarding, what management say are unfound allegations, EOH reported strong year end financial results with 21% growth in revenue and 16% growth in headline earnings per share.\r\n\r\nGlobally, most markets ended the week higher. Dow Jones (+0.36%), S&amp;P 500 (+0.08%), STOXX 600 (+0.66%), FTSE 100 (+1.32%) and TOPIX (+1.57%) all showed weekly gains. The NASDAQ, however, fell 0.33% for the week.\r\n\r\nThe Federal Reserve announced that it will begin its balance-sheet normalization program next month. US interest rates were left unchanged, but 11 of the 16 members of the Fed’s rate-setting committee still expect one more hike in 2017. Most analysts seem to think this will take place in December.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, the Fed said that it would keep the target range for its federal funds rate at 1.00%-1.25%, noting that the labor market still remains strong and inflation remains below its 2.0% target. The 2-year and 10-year Treasury yields, along with the dollar, rose after the Fed\'s announcement.\r\n\r\nLastly, German voters are going to the polls on Sunday amid predictions that the country’s far-right will win seats in the Bundestag for the first time in half a century. Early signs suggested a surge in voter turnout on previous elections – but it was unclear whether this would benefit the Government or opposition parties.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Market Moves of the Week:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_733\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"496\"]<img class=\"wp-image-733 size-full\" src=\"http://strategiq.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/mm.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"496\" height=\"520\" /> Source: Thomson Reuters[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Chart of the Week:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_734\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"607\"]<img class=\"wp-image-734 size-full\" src=\"http://strategiq.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/cpi.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"607\" height=\"423\" /> The South African Reserve Bank (SARB) left its key policy rate unchanged at 6.75%. The MPC was split 3-3 on whether to ease or hold, suggesting the barrier to further easing later in the year is low.[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAs always we welcome any feedback on our Weekly Review.\r\n\r\nHave a great week!\r\n\r\n<em>The information included above as well as individual companies and/or securities mentioned should not be construed as investment advice, a recommendation to buy or sell or an indication of trading intent on behalf of any Strategiq product. Strategiq Capital is an authorised financial services provider (FSP 46624).</em>','Week in Review: Rates Remain Unchanged','','publish','open','open','','week-review-rates-remain-unchanged','','','2017-09-25 10:19:35','2017-09-25 08:19:35','',0,'http://strategiq.co.za/?p=