	(754,2,'2017-10-07 12:44:27','2017-10-07 10:44:27','All three benchmark US equity indices touched record highs this week, helped by encouraging economic data releases that showed stronger-than-expected trends in the manufacturing and services sectors, as well as auto sales.\r\n\r\nSouth Africa’s share indexes also posted record high closes for the second straight day on Friday, with the rand slipping after U.S. jobs data, the All-share index added 0.41 percent to end the week at 57,231.\r\n\r\nE-commerce group Naspers, which has a one-third stake in Hong Kong-listed Tencent, hit an all-time high and closed 0.90 percent higher at 3,164.69 rand on the back of gains in the Chinese internet company.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIn other company news cement producer PPC closed lower after it said that Nigeria’s Dangote Cement had withdrawn its interest in a tie-up.\r\n\r\nThe rand was 0.44 percent weaker, after earlier in the day hitting its lowest since mid-April at 13.8125. The rand has fallen over 5% against the dollar since the start of last month.\r\n\r\nThe U.S. jobs report showed a fall in employment in September because of Hurricanes Harvey and Irma, but a rise in wages could boost inflation and provide an argument for the Fed to tighten policy soon.\r\n\r\nThe unemployment rate fell to 4.2%, signalling that the labour market continues to operate at or below “full employment.” Wages grew by 2.9% year-over-year in September, the fastest pace since 2009 and a welcome increase over the 2.6% average wage growth over the past two years.\r\n\r\nBritish Prime Minister Theresa May continued to feel the pressure at the Conservatives Party’s annual conference in Manchester this week. Sterling was set to deliver its worst weekly performance in a year after Mrs May’s speech sparked uncertainty over the prime minister’s future.\r\n\r\nTensions are running high in Spain with the ramifications of the referendum in Catalonia been felt in the Spanish equity and bond markets. The Barcelona-based Catalan government has threatened to secede in the coming days.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Market Moves of the Week:</strong></p>\r\n<img class=\"size-full wp-image-758 aligncenter\" src=\"http://strategiq.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/week.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"513\" height=\"552\" />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Chart of the Week:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_759\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"677\"]<img class=\"size-full wp-image-759\" src=\"http://strategiq.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/pic33.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"677\" height=\"466\" /> Source: Thomson Reuters. Fridays\'s jobs report may have shown a 33,000 drop in US nonfarm payroll employment in September, but the US dollar, Treasury yields and the probabilities that investors assign to a rate increase in December all rose.[/caption]\r\n\r\nAs always we welcome any feedback on our Weekly Review.\r\n\r\nHave a great week!\r\n\r\n<em>The information included above as well as individual companies and/or securities mentioned should not be construed as investment advice, a recommendation to buy or sell or an indication of trading intent on behalf of any Strategiq product. Strategiq Capital is an authorised financial services provider (FSP 46624).</em>','Week in Review: New Highs','','publish','open','open','','week-review-new-highs','','','2017-10-07 12:49:17','2017-10-07 10:49:17','',0,'http://strategiq.co.za/?p=754',0,'post','',0),
