	(777,2,'2017-10-22 14:04:33','2017-10-22 12:04:33','The JSE All-Share index (+0.12%) ended the week relatively flat. Resources (+0.53%) and Industrials (+0.47%) were positive, supported by the weaker rand (+2.84%), while Financials (-0.89%) and SA Listed Property (-0.37%) decreased.\r\n\r\nPresident Jacob Zuma once again surprised the market with a Cabinet reshuffle. This is the second surprise reshuffle of 2017, and the weakening rand represents investors heightened political concern. Of the six changes made to Cabinet, most notable was the removal of  Blade Nzimande from the higher education and training ministry and the placement of a pro-nuclear and presidential loyalist David Mahlobo as minister of energy.\r\n\r\nFurther, investors remained generally cautious ahead of Finance Minister Malusi Gigaba’s medium term budget policy statement next week. Loose fiscal spending remains a concern.\r\n\r\nIn company news, Discovery finally announced that the company has been granted a banking licence – a potential catalyst to future earnings growth. Pick n Pay reported a drop in half-year earnings after cutting jobs as part of an intensifying price battle with rivals in a weak economy. However, excluding severance costs, earnings rose 13%. Pick n Pay has changed its sales model to focus on pushing “in-house” private label products in an effort to increase margins going forward.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Market Moves of the Week:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_778\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"519\"]<img class=\"wp-image-778\" src=\"http://strategiq.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/week-update.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"519\" height=\"549\" /> Source: Thomson Reuters[/caption]\r\n\r\nGlobally, the Dow Jones (+2.00%), S&amp;P 500 (+0.86%) and NASDAQ (+0.35%) all ended the week in the green. While the STOXX 600 and FTSE 100 fell 0.33% and 0.16% respectively.\r\n\r\nUS large-cap stocks continued their rally, reaching record highs for the sixth week in a row. Rising company earnings and easing political uncertainty as the Senate passed a 2018 budget resolution continued to support market gains going forward. The majority of company earnings are set to come out over the next two weeks, with earnings expected to continue to rise but reports could prompt volatility in individual stocks. Lastly, new home sales and GDP for the third quarter are events investors should look out for next week.\r\n\r\nThe UK market continued to come under pressure with the bulk of the loss coming towards the end of the week. Among the biggest fallers was Unilever, which fell after announcing disappointing third-quarter earnings.  The recent hurricanes in the US hit their ice-cream brands hard as well as continued wet weather in Europe and a loss of market share to low-calorie rival Halo Top.\r\n\r\nIn Japan, prime minister Shinzo Abe’s ruling coalition may win a two-thirds majority in Sunday’s general election, increasing his chances at becoming Japan’s longest-serving leader. This win would pave the way for more ultra-easy monetary policy and flexible fiscal stimulus that has helped Asia’s second biggest economy grow for six straight quarters. Further, it would give Donald Trump a reliable partner in pushing a hard-line stance against Km Jong Un’s regime in North Korea.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Market Moves of the Week:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_779\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"517\"]<img class=\"wp-image-779 size-full\" src=\"http://strategiq.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/week-update-1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"517\" height=\"401\" /> US stocks as a whole are by no means cheap today, as the S&amp;P 500 currently trades at 23.5 times trailing earnings, above the longer-term average and reflective of solid earnings growth forecasts.[/caption]\r\n\r\nAs always we welcome any feedback on our Weekly Review.\r\n\r\nHave a great week!\r\n\r\n<em>The information included above as well as in