	(784,2,'2017-10-29 13:17:21','2017-10-29 11:17:21','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The JSE All-Share index (+1.32%) ended the week considerably stronger amid gains in Resources (+2.27%) and Industrials (2.47%). The two markets are responding to the currency movement over the week as a response to a lacklustre budget performance meeting which was held on Wednesday. The rand depreciated by 3.10% relative to the dollar for the week, making rand hedge industrials and resources an attractive trade. Financials (-1.82%) and SA Listed Property (-2.07%) were negatively impacted by the news over the week.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Locally, the highlight of the week was of course Finance Minister Malusi Gigaba’s maiden budget performance speech. Unfortunately, the budget performance did not leave anybody wanting to celebrate. South Africa GDP forecast was slashed to 0.7% from 1.3%, the projected revenue shortfall was higher than expected at R50.8bn widening the budget deficit from 3.1% to 4.3% in 2017 and debt-to-GDP is now estimated to increase to 60%, from 54% by 2022. Perhaps one of the most disappointing takeaways from the speech was that there doesn’t seem to be any considerable plan or measure to stimulate growth. There was no mention of tax hikes or plans for new tax hikes which leaves investors in the dark. Taking all of the above into account, the probability of a credit rating downgrade seems more likely. If the credit rating downgrade does take place, the market can expect a weaker rand, a possible interest rate hike to combat the rising inflation and overall, lower confidence in South Africa.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Market Moves of the Week:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_787\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"681\"]<img class=\"wp-image-787 size-full\" src=\"http://strategiq.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/Picture1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"681\" height=\"712\" /> Source: Thomson Reuters[/caption]\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Globally, the majority of markets finished the week positively, the Dow Jones (+0.45%), S&amp;P 500 (+0.23%), NASDAQ (+1.09%), STOXX 600 (+0.85%) and the TOPIX (+2.33%) all ended the week in the green. The technology-heavy NASDAQ benefited from a strong set of earnings results from companies such as Amazon, Alphabet (Google’s parent company), Twitter and Microsoft, all of whom beat market expectations.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Commodities had a mixed week with brent crude (+4.66%) ending the week stronger, hitting $60 a barrel on Friday for the first time in more than two years, boosted by geopolitical tension and expectations that exporters will extend the OPEC-led output cuts. Gold (-0.70%), iron ore (-0.26%) and platinum (-1.46%) all ended the week softer.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In company specific news, Amazon was the biggest winner of the week. The share jumped 13.22% on Friday as a response to its earnings and revenue beat. Amazon reported a Q3 revenue increase of 34% beating market expectations by 3.7%. The fast growing technology group also beat on earnings by posting $0.52/share vs. the market expectation of $0.03/share. The Amazon Web Services (cloud computing storage) remains the groups growth driver as the company continues to expand its retail offering around the world.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Chart of the Week:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_790\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"615\"]<img class=\"wp-image-790 size-full\" src=\"http://strategiq.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/Screenshot_1-e1509274828418.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"615\" height=\"430\" /> This chart represents the gross debt-to-GDP outlook. By 2020/2021 nearly 15% of the main budget will be spent servicing debt. The National Treasury estimates that stabilising gross debt-to-GDP below 60% will require spending cuts or tax rate hikes.[/caption]\r\n\r\nAs always we welcome any feedback on our Weekly Review.\r\n\r\nHave a great week!\r\n\r\n<em>The information included above as well as individual companies and/or securities mentioned should not be construed as investment advice, a recommendation to buy or sell or an indication of trading intent on behalf of any Strategiq product. Strategiq Capital is an authorised financial services provider (FSP 46624).</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Week in Review: Gigaba\'s Maiden Voyage','','publish','open','open','','week-review-gigabas-maiden-voyage','','','2017-10-29 13:48:46','2017-10-29 11:48:46','',0,'http://strategiq.co.za/?p=784',0,'post','',0),
